    "lesson_content_markdown":  "# Matching the Subject and Action\n\nTo speak English correctly, you must match your **Subject** (the person or thing) with your **Action Word** (the verb). We call this Subject-Verb Agreement.\n\n### 1. The Golden Rule of -s\n\nIn the Present Simple, we add an **-s** to the action word if the subject is **He**, **She**, or **It** (one person or thing).\n\n- **I, You, We, They** â†’ No extra letter (eat, play, study)\n- **He, She, It** â†’ Add **-s** (eats, plays, studies)\n\n### 2. Examples with People\n\n- **My teacher** (She) â†’ **gives** a lot of homework.\n- **The students** (They) â†’ **give** a lot of homework. (Wait! This is wrong. Students do not give homework, they receive it!)\n- **The student** (He) â†’ **receives** a high score.\n\n### 3. Examples with Things\n\n- **The bus** (It) â†’ **stops** at the gate.\n- **The buses** (They) â†’ **stop** at the gate.\n- **The math book** (It) â†’ **cost** fifty dollars. (Error! Should be **costs**)\n\n### 4. Why is it important?\n\nNative speakers use this rule every time they speak. If you miss the **-s**, it is the most common mistake for learners.\n\n- **Correct**: He **likes** the game.\n- **Incorrect**: He **like** the game.\n\n---",
